<heading id="713081A7196229417481F9FDFEFDF9B4" box="[211,319,1596,1619]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" reason="5">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9196229417481F9FDFEFDF9B4" box="[211,319,1596,1619]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A7836CB196229417481F9A2FB51F97C" blockId="50.[211,1171,1596,1691]" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">
Differs from 
<taxonomicName id="EDC74D48196229417538F9A5FE2AF99C" authority="Santos &amp; Melo, 2014" authorityName="Santos &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" box="[362,488,1636,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guarani" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9196229417538F9A5FE2AF99C" box="[362,488,1636,1659]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">M. guarani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="038057A21962294175A2F9A5FDECF99C" box="[496,558,1636,1659]" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EDC74D4819622941763BF9A5FD3AF99B" authority="Santos &amp; Melo, 2014" authorityName="Santos &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" box="[617,760,1636,1660]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karitiana" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD919622941763BF9A5FD3AF99B" box="[617,760,1636,1660]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">M. karitiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="038057A2196229417752F9A5FCFCF99C" box="[768,830,1636,1659]" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by medial protruding process of S4 digitiform in lateral view; from 
<taxonomicName id="EDC74D481962294176D3F945FCC9F97C" authorityName="Santos and Silveira" authorityYear="2009" box="[641,779,1667,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlantica">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD91962294176D3F945FCC9F97C" box="[641,779,1667,1691]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">M. atlantica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EDC74D48196229417749F945FC73F97C" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1879" box="[795,945,1668,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurata">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9196229417749F945FC73F97C" box="[795,945,1668,1691]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">M. purpurata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EDC74D481962294177BFF945FB51F97C" authorityName="Santos &amp; Melo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1005,1171,1668,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Megalopta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="625" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mapinguari">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD91962294177BFF945FB51F97C" box="[1005,1171,1668,1691]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="625">M. mapinguari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A7836CB1963294074C2FF68FE10FF07" blockId="51.[144,1103,168,224]" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">
sp. n. by integument mostly reddish brown with metallic green tints on head and mesosoma (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E196329407544FF09FE51FF07" box="[278,403,200,224]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[212,279,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1366]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[212,1172,168,1371]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Females of Megalopta. (A, F) Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (B, D) dorsal view of mesoscutum; (C, E) lateral view of mesosoma; (A) M. mura sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (B, C) M. guimaraesi Santos &amp; Silveira from Alto Paraíso de Goiás, Brazil; (D, E) M. mura sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (F) M. xavante sp. n. (holotype) from Nova Xavantina, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004465/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figures 3F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294075F1FF09FE00FF07" box="[419,450,200,224]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[144,211,1402,1424]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[144,1104,168,1370]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Females of Megalopta. (A‒E) Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) Megalopta yanomami sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (B) M. piraha sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (C) M. munduruku sp. n. from Belterra, Brazil; (D) M. cuprea Friese from Nigrillani, Bolivia; (E) M. sodalis Vachal from Antonina, Brazil; (F) frontal view of head of M. xavante sp. n from Nova Xavantina, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004467" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004467/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">4F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62DD65401963294074C2FEEDFCC8FA56" pageId="51" pageNumber="626" type="description">
<paragraph id="2A7836CB1963294074C2FEEDFECDFEA4" blockId="51.[144,1104,300,1287]" box="[144,271,300,323]" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">
<heading id="713081A71963294074C2FEEDFECDFEA4" box="[144,271,300,323]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="51" pageNumber="626" reason="5">
<emphasis id="18B3EAD91963294074C2FEEDFECDFEA4" box="[144,271,300,323]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A7836CB1963294074C2FE93FCC1FAE0" blockId="51.[144,1104,300,1287]" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">
(1) Mandible simple and lacking supplementary teeth (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E196329407757FE93FCBAFE8D" box="[773,888,338,362]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[144,211,1402,1424]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[144,1104,168,1370]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Females of Megalopta. (A‒E) Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) Megalopta yanomami sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (B) M. piraha sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (C) M. munduruku sp. n. from Belterra, Brazil; (D) M. cuprea Friese from Nigrillani, Bolivia; (E) M. sodalis Vachal from Antonina, Brazil; (F) frontal view of head of M. xavante sp. n from Nova Xavantina, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004467" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004467/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 4F</figureCitation>
). (2) Labral elevation in central portion, with rounded elevated area in relation to the sides. (2) Clypeus with surface between punctures on basal and central area smooth, the apical macula reddish brown. (4) Central portion of supraclypeal area with sparse punctation, punctures separated by 
<emphasis id="18B3EAD91963294075F6FE12FE73FE0D" box="[420,433,467,490]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">≥</emphasis>
1 pd. (5) Antenna reddish brown (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E196329407702FE13FC06FE0D" box="[848,964,466,490]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[144,211,1402,1424]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[144,1104,168,1370]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Females of Megalopta. (A‒E) Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) Megalopta yanomami sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (B) M. piraha sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (C) M. munduruku sp. n. from Belterra, Brazil; (D) M. cuprea Friese from Nigrillani, Bolivia; (E) M. sodalis Vachal from Antonina, Brazil; (F) frontal view of head of M. xavante sp. n from Nova Xavantina, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004467" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004467/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 4F</figureCitation>
). (6) Upper frons flat, not strongly declivous toward sulcus around median ocellus. (7) Ocellocular distance equal to length of F1 (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294076D7FDD3FD3AFDCD" box="[645,760,530,554]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="9.[144,211,1402,1424]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[144,1104,168,1370]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 4. Females of Megalopta. (A‒E) Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) Megalopta yanomami sp. n. from Parauapebas, Brazil; (B) M. piraha sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (C) M. munduruku sp. n. from Belterra, Brazil; (D) M. cuprea Friese from Nigrillani, Bolivia; (E) M. sodalis Vachal from Antonina, Brazil; (F) frontal view of head of M. xavante sp. n from Nova Xavantina, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004467" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004467/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 4F</figureCitation>
). (8) Mesoscutum adjacent to the parapsidial line densely punctured, punctures contiguous, punctation becoming sparser towards the mesoscutal lip (&lt;1 pd). (9) Scutellum with posterior margin raised in relation to anterior margin of metanotum. (10). Metanotum with integument, in oblique view, not hidden by short plumose pilosity. (11) Basal area of metapostnotum reddish brown, its length 0.4× that of metanotum, with smooth surface, without longitudinal rugulosities (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E196329407623FD10FD21FD0E" box="[625,739,721,745]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[212,279,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1366]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[212,1172,168,1371]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Females of Megalopta. (A, F) Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (B, D) dorsal view of mesoscutum; (C, E) lateral view of mesosoma; (A) M. mura sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (B, C) M. guimaraesi Santos &amp; Silveira from Alto Paraíso de Goiás, Brazil; (D, E) M. mura sp. n. from Manaus, Brazil; (F) M. xavante sp. n. (holotype) from Nova Xavantina, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004465/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 3F</figureCitation>
). (12) Mesepisternum with contiguous punctation. (13) Metepisternum with sparse pilosity, integument visible through pilosity, posterior upper margin unmodified, lacking a velvety process. (14) T1 with dorsal surface of disc sparsely punctured (
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9196329407688FCF0FD25FCAF" box="[730,743,817,840]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">≥</emphasis>
1 pd), posterior marginal zone microreticulated between punctures. 
<emphasis id="18B3EAD9196329407662FC90FDA8FC8E" box="[560,618,849,873]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Male</emphasis>
. (15) Scape with diameter gradually enlarging toward the apex (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294075C7FCB1FDC5FC6F" box="[405,519,880,904]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="16.[212,279,1399,1421]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1367]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[212,1172,168,1367]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 9. Males of Megalopta. (A) Dorsal view of flagellum of M. guimaraesi from Formosa, Brazil; (B) ventral view of sternum 3‒4 of M. amoena from Alenquer, Brazil; (C, E) dorsal view of head; (D, F) Frontal view of head; (C) M. guarani sp. n. from Chapada dos Guimarães, Brazil; (D) M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (E) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (F) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004477/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 9E</figureCitation>
). (16) Flagellum reddish brown, except F2 and F3 lighter than the others (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294075CEFC51FDCCFC4F" box="[412,526,912,936]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="16.[212,279,1399,1421]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1367]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[212,1172,168,1367]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 9. Males of Megalopta. (A) Dorsal view of flagellum of M. guimaraesi from Formosa, Brazil; (B) ventral view of sternum 3‒4 of M. amoena from Alenquer, Brazil; (C, E) dorsal view of head; (D, F) Frontal view of head; (C) M. guarani sp. n. from Chapada dos Guimarães, Brazil; (D) M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (E) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (F) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004477/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 9E</figureCitation>
); F1–F11 not differing in diameter; F2 about twothirds of F 
<quantity id="ED3F9B2E19632940755FFC71FEF8FC2F" box="[269,314,944,968]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="51" pageNumber="626" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
length (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294075CEFC71FDCDFC2F" box="[412,527,944,968]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="16.[212,279,1399,1421]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,1367]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[212,1172,168,1367]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 9. Males of Megalopta. (A) Dorsal view of flagellum of M. guimaraesi from Formosa, Brazil; (B) ventral view of sternum 3‒4 of M. amoena from Alenquer, Brazil; (C, E) dorsal view of head; (D, F) Frontal view of head; (C) M. guarani sp. n. from Chapada dos Guimarães, Brazil; (D) M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (E) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (F) M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004477/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 9E</figureCitation>
); F6–F11, in anterior view, with the anterior and posterior margins flat, in posterior view with basal glabrous area at same level of remaining surface. (17) Metanotum with integument, in dorsal view, not hidden by short plumose pilosity (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294075FFFBD1FDF4FBCF" box="[429,566,1040,1064]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="19.[144,213,1405,1427]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[144,1104,168,1373]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 11. Males of Megalopta. (A, C, D). Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) M. karitiana sp. n. from Ouro Preto do Oeste, Brazil; (B) ventral view of sternum 3‒4 of M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (C) M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (D) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (E) dorsal view of mesosoma of M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil; (F) posterior view of mesosoma of M. purpurata Smith (holotype) from Tefé, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004481/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 11D</figureCitation>
). (18) Basal area of metapostnotum reddish brown with metallic green tints; its length about 0.7× that of metanotum; the longitudinal rugulosities slightly impressed centrally (
<figureCitation id="B2FC2A4E1963294076EAFB91FCF8FB8F" box="[696,826,1104,1128]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="19.[144,213,1405,1427]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[144,1104,168,1373]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 11. Males of Megalopta. (A, C, D). Posterolateral view of mesosoma; (A) M. karitiana sp. n. from Ouro Preto do Oeste, Brazil; (B) ventral view of sternum 3‒4 of M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (C) M. mapinguari sp. n. from Rio Branco, Brazil; (D) M. xavante sp. n. from Nova Xavantina, Brazil; (E) dorsal view of mesosoma of M. atlantica Santos &amp; Silveira from Ipanema, Brazil; (F) posterior view of mesosoma of M. purpurata Smith (holotype) from Tefé, Brazil. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4004481" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4004481/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="626">Figure 11D</figureCitation>
). (19) Metepisternum as in the female. (20) 1st and 2nd tarsomeres of foreleg with longest simple setae shorter than summed length of the three apical tarsomeres. (21) S3 with longitudinal sulcus, posterolateral margin notched. (22) S4 with medial protruding process, profile of process digitiform in lateral view; basal portion glabrous; posterolateral margin notched, notched not extended to basal half of sclerite.
</paragraph>
